Significance of mud pack on egg clutches. Parental care in amphibians is the energy investment into offspring after fertilisation (for details refer to
Wells 2007
). Egg attendance by male individuals has been attributed to protection of eggs from being damaged by intruding males, and deterring egg predation and preventing desiccation (in
Hyalinobatrachium valerioi (
Vockenhuber et al. 2009
))
. Parental care involving both male and female, only females and only males are well known (
Wells 2007
). So far, there is no report of any other anuran species covering egg clutch with mud. Mud packing on egg clutches by
N. kumbara
might be attributed to, 1 . minimising clutch dehydration as the outer capsule of terrestrial amphibian eggs are susceptible to dehydration by losing moisture to drier air (
Duellman & Trueb 1994
), 2 . camouflage eggs as the eggs are very prominently pigmented to avoid predators (
Crump 1995
;
Wells 2007
).
